@page "/"
@{
    Layout = null;
}

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>babble &mdash; Language Guide</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="console_dark.css">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="documentation.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div id="cover"></div>

    <div id="heroWrapper">
        <div id="logoHero">
            <div id="heroTitle"><span style="color: var(--color-red)">(</span><span style="color: var(--color-seagreen)">bab</span><br/>&nbsp;<span style="color: var(--color-seagreen)">ble</span><span style="color: var(--color-red)">)</span></div>
            <div class="hero-img-wrap">
                <img src="babble_red.svg" id="heroImg" alt="babble">
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="cmdWindow">
        <div class="guide-wrap">

            <!-- ── What is babble? ─────────────────────────────── -->
            <div class="section" id="what">
                <p><code class="babble-code">(babble)</code> is a dynamic, general-purpose language with a single, persistent, <i>globally global</i> namespace. In <code class="babble-code">(babble)</code>, there are no modules, no packages. Every term you define is stored in a server-side lexicon, immediately available to every other user.</p>

                <p>If you define <code class="babble-code">double</code>, perhaps with the command <code class="babble-code">(define double [x] (* 2 x))</code>, then Congratulations! You've contributed to the standard library; your new term is declared not only in your local session, but across all <code class="babble-code">(babble)</code> code running anywhere.</p>

                <div class="inset-highlight">
                    <p><a href="/console/">Try the babble console</a></p>
                </div>

                <p><code class="babble-code">(babble)</code> borrows its syntax and code-as-data philosophy from Clojure: functions are first-class and written as s-expressions.</p>
                <p>Terms can be renamed or reorganized individually or through <i>dialects</i>, systematic renaming proposals approved and incorporated into the main language. These rely on community consensus, working with an assumption of good faith.</p>
            </div>

            <!-- ── Syntax ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
            <div class="section" id="syntax">
                <div class="section-title">Syntax</div>
                <p><span class="babble-code"><code class="babble-code">(babble)</code></span> uses Lispy syntax and encourages a tacit, pure style. Every expression is wrapped in parentheses, with the function name first, followed by its arguments:</p>

                <div class="code-block babble-code">(+ 1 2)                     ; => 3
(str "hello" " world")      ; => "hello world"
(if (> 3 2) "yes" "no")     ; => "yes"</div>

                <p>Vectors use square brackets. They appear mainly in parameter lists and <code class="babble-code">let</code> bindings.</p>
                <div class="code-block babble-code">[x y z]           ; a vector of three symbols

(let [a 10  b 20]
  (+ a b))          ; => 30</div>

                <p>Strings are double-quoted. Numbers may be integers or floats, and may include a leading sign.</p>
                <div class="code-block babble-code">"hello"   42   3.14   -7   +1.5</div>


            </div>

            <!-- ── Defining Terms ─────────────────────────────── -->
            <div class="section" id="defining">
                <div class="section-title">Defining Terms</div>
                <p>Use <code class="babble-code">define</code> to add a new term to the lexicon. The general form is:</p>

                <div class="code-block babble-code">(define name "optional docstring" [param1 param2 …]
  body-expression)</div>

                <div class="example-grid">
                    <div class="example-card">
                        <div class="label">Value (no params)</div>
                        <pre class="babble-code">(define tau
  (* 2 3.14159))</pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="example-card">
                        <div class="label">Function (with params)</div>
                        <pre class="babble-code">(define double
  [x]
  (* 2 x))</pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="example-card">
                        <div class="label">With docstring</div>
                        <pre class="babble-code">(define square
  "Returns x squared."
  [x]
  (* x x))</pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="example-card">
                        <div class="label">Using other terms</div>
                        <pre class="babble-code">(define quad
  [x]
  (square (square x)))</pre>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <p>Terms at different arities are stored separately. You can define <code class="babble-code">add</code> for one argument and again for two:</p>
                <div class="code-block babble-code">(define add [x]   (+ x 0))
(define add [x y] (+ x y))</div>

                <div class="callout">
                    <strong>Always think of Names as permanent.</strong> Once a term is defined, it is essentially part of the language, and can't easily be redefined or renamed.
                </div>

                <p>There is nothing like this <code class="babble-code">defn</code> construction in <code class="babble-code">(babble)</code>:</p>

                <div class="error-inset">
                    <pre class="babble-code">(defn f [x]
  (-> x
      (inc)
      (* 3)
      (str "!")))</pre>
                </div>
                <p>Instead, we use a more concise, point-free style:</p>

                <div class="code-block babble-code">(define f [x] (comp #(str % "!") #(* % 3) inc))
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- ── Using Terms ────────────────────────────────── -->
            <div class="section" id="using">
                <div class="section-title">Using Terms</div>
                <p>Call any term by placing its name in the function position of a list, followed by the arguments.</p>

                <div class="code-block babble-code">(double 21)                      ; => 42
(square 9)                       ; => 81
(add 3 4)                        ; => 7
(+ (double 5) (square 3))        ; => 19</div>

                <p>Terms can be combined freely with built-in Clojure functions. The full set of available built-ins &mdash; arithmetic, collections, strings, higher-order functions &mdash; is the same as in Clojure/SCI.</p>

                <div class="code-block babble-code">(map double [1 2 3 4])          ; => (2 4 6 8)
(filter odd? [1 2 3 4 5])       ; => (1 3 5)
(reduce add [10 20 30])         ; => 60</div>
            </div>

            <!-- ── Command Reference ──────────────────────────── -->
            <div class="section" id="reference">
                <div class="section-title">Lexicon</div>
                <table class="cmd-table">
                    <tr>
                        <td><code class="babble-code">(define name [params] body)</code></td>
                        <td>Register a new term. Params list may be empty <code class="babble-code">[]</code>. An optional docstring can appear between the name and the params.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code class="babble-code">(source name)</code></td>
                        <td>Print the original source line for every arity of <code class="babble-code">name</code>.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code class="babble-code">(doc name)</code></td>
                        <td>Print the docstring for <code class="babble-code">name</code>. Aliases: <code class="babble-code">desc</code>, <code class="babble-code">man</code>.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code class="babble-code">(handle username)</code></td>
                        <td>Set your handle. Your name will appear in the prompt and be recorded with any terms you define.</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code class="babble-code">(about)</code></td>
                        <td>Display server name, version, and build date.</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

            </div>

        </div><!-- /guide-wrap -->
    </div><!-- /cmdWindow -->

    <footer class="site-footer">
        <div class="footer-inner">
            <div>
                <div><code class="babble-code">(babble)</code></div>
                <div class="foot_gb">Created by <a href="https://danieltemkin.com">Daniel Temkin</a>, 2023</div>
                <div class="foot_gb">One of <a href="https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262553087/forty-four-esolangs/">Forty-Four Esolangs</a> (MIT Press)</div>
            </div>
            
            <span class="footer-right foot_gb"><a href="/console/">Open the console</a></span>
        </div>
    </footer>

    <script src="syntax-highlighter.js"></script>
    <script>
        // Hero collapse animation
        (function () {
            // babble_red.svg natural dimensions: 193 × 208
            var ASPECT = 193 / 208;

            // stripes start 3× natural size
            var STRIPE_SCALE_START = 3;

            var heroEl = document.getElementById('logoHero');
            var heroTitle = document.getElementById('heroTitle');

            function update() {
                var vhPx = window.innerHeight;
                var vwPx = window.innerWidth;

                // Target: image fills the left gutter between the left edge and the center column

                // Center column is max-width:860px, so gutter = (viewport - 860) / 2. Subtract 50px so the hero's right edge clears the column's left padding.
                var gapWidth = Math.max(80, (vwPx - 860) / 2 - 50);

                // Compute the final hero height so the image (height:100%, width:auto) to exactly fill gapWidth at the collapsed state.
                var finalImgH = gapWidth / ASPECT;
                var HERO_MIN = finalImgH + 40;  // +40 for the 20px top/bottom offsets

                var dist = vhPx - HERO_MIN;
                if (dist <= 0) return;
                var progress = Math.min(1, Math.max(0, window.scrollY / dist));

                // Hero height: image is height:100%, so image height tracks hero height
                heroEl.style.height = (vhPx - dist * progress - 40) + 'px';

                // Hero width: collapse from (viewport - 20px) down to gapWidth
                var w0 = vwPx - 20;
                heroEl.style.width = (w0 + (gapWidth - w0) * progress) + 'px';

                // Title fades out in the first 40% of the collapse
                heroTitle.style.opacity = Math.max(0, 1 - progress / 0.4).toFixed(3);
            }

            window.addEventListener('scroll', update, { passive: true });
            window.addEventListener('resize', update);
            update();
        })();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
